5.3. Angle Bisectors in Triangles www.ck12.org
Example A
Is Y on the angle bisector of 6 XWZ?
If Y is on the angle bisector, then XY = Y Z and both segments need to be perpendicular to the sides of the angle.
From the markings we know XY ⊥−−→WX and ZY ⊥−→WZ. Second, XY =Y Z = 6. So, yes, Y is on the angle bisector of
6 XWZ.
Example B
−→
MO is the angle bisector of 6 LMN. Find the measure of x.
LO = ON by the Angle Bisector Theorem.
4x−5 = 23
4x = 28
x = 7
Example C
−→
AB is the angle bisector of 6 CAD. Solve for the missing variable.
252
www.ck12.org Chapter 5. Triangle Relationships
CB = BD by the Angle Bisector Theorem, so we can set up and solve an equation for x.
x+7 = 2(3x−4)
x+7 = 6x−8
15 = 5x
x = 3
